      "comment_id" : 133573094,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "<code>escapeHtml4</code> has been moved to org.apache.commons.text.StringEscapeUtils."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 212615,
      "reputation" : 4986,
      "user_id" : 465545,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 86,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1502d7c77aaf2b238c7a5506867abf76?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Martin Dimitrov",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/465545/martin-dimitrov"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 48,
    "last_activity_date" : 1379913245,
    "last_edit_date" : 1379913245,
    "creation_date" : 1311087486,
    "answer_id" : 6749280,
    "question_id" : 1265282,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>There is a newer version of the <a href=\"http://commons.apache.org/proper/commons-lang/javadocs/api-3.0/index.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Apache Commons Lang library</a> and it uses a different package name (org.apache.commons.lang3). The <code>StringEscapeUtils</code> now has different static methods for escaping different types of documents (<a href=\"http://commons.apache.org/proper/commons-lang/javadocs/api-3.0/index.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://commons.apache.org/proper/commons-lang/javadocs/api-3.0/index.html</a>). So to escape HTML version 4.0 string:</p>\n\n<pre><code>import static org.apache.commons.lang3.StringEscapeUtils.escapeHtml4;\n\nString output = escapeHtml4(\"The less than sign (&lt;) and ampersand (&amp;) must be escaped before using them in HTML\");\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 24823,
        "reputation" : 3154,
        "user_id" : 63369,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 71,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1bc2471f5a97b66082c3522697078ef7?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "Roboprog",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/63369/roboprog"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 6,
      "creation_date" : 1367284039,
      "post_id" : 14900233,
      "comment_id" : 23318698,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "THANK YOU for pointing out that the <i>context</i> in which you wish to encode the output very much matters.  The term &quot;encode&quot; is also a much more appropriate verb than &quot;escape&quot;, as well.  Escape implies some kind of special hack, as opposed to &quot;how do I <i>encode</i> this string for: an XHTML attribute / SQL query parameter / PostScript print string / CSV output field?"
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 38529,
        "reputation" : 951,
        "user_id" : 110642,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c5afd551da659f0aa7fb04b6d9e4f383?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "Jeff Williams",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/110642/jeff-williams"
      },
      "reply_to_user" : {
        "account_id" : 24823,
        "reputation" : 3154,
        "user_id" : 63369,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 71,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1bc2471f5a97b66082c3522697078ef7?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "Roboprog",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/63369/roboprog"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 5,
      "creation_date" : 1395248337,
      "post_id" : 14900233,
      "comment_id" : 34254036,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "&#39;Encode&#39; and &#39;escape&#39; are both widely used to describe this. The term &quot;escape&quot; is generally used when the process is to add an &quot;escape character&quot; before a syntactically-relevant character, such as escaping a quote character with a backslash \\&quot;   The term &quot;encode&quot; is more typically used when you translate a character into a different form, such as URL encoding the quote character %22 or HTML entity encoding as &amp;#x22 or @quot."
    }, {
