    "creation_date" : 1365154883,
    "answer_id" : 15830614,
    "question_id" : 1265282,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>On android (API 16 or greater) you can:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Html.escapeHtml(textToScape);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>or for lower API:</p>\n\n<pre><code>TextUtils.htmlEncode(textToScape);\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 123612,
      "reputation" : 49188,
      "user_id" : 318174,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 71,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/916b39039a8269e3c45b5ce2b98675a9?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Adam Gent",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/318174/adam-gent"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 14,
    "last_activity_date" : 1375907170,
    "creation_date" : 1375907170,
    "answer_id" : 18113158,
    "question_id" : 1265282,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>While @dfa answer of <code>org.apache.commons.lang.StringEscapeUtils.escapeHtml</code> is nice and I have used it in the past it should not be used for escaping HTML (or XML) <strong>attributes</strong> otherwise the whitespace will be normalized (meaning all adjacent whitespace characters become a single space).</p>\n\n<p>I know this because I have had bugs filed against my library (JATL) for attributes where whitespace was not preserved. Thus I have a drop in (copy n' paste) <a href=\"https://code.google.com/p/jatl/source/browse/src/main/java/com/googlecode/jatl/MarkupUtils.java\" rel=\"noreferrer\">class (of which I stole some from JDOM) that differentiates the escaping of attributes and element content</a>.</p>\n\n<p>While this may not have mattered as much in the past (proper attribute escaping) it is increasingly become of greater interest given the use use of HTML5's <code>data-</code> attribute usage.</p>\n"
  }, {
